Anonymous Sun 14 Apr 2019 14:30:37 No.22503124 Report
Quoted By: >>22503663 >>22506797 >>22508550 >>22510657
Alright, I'm going to go into a bit of an autism fit but it needs to be stated:

The General is messed up. Snake Nonsense by Kaktus-Nsfw was updated last thread and yet it's still around the middle of the story list instead of the top, second only to Scavenging for love. For awhile now there have been a lot of little mistakes happening with the OP and it's becoming more and more persistent: new or updated stories not going up at all or not going to where they need to be, or the archive link not linking to the past thread but to the thread before it because it was copy and pasted from said thread.
Writefags will be less motivated to write here if they're constantly wondering whether the next general is going to miss their work by mistake and it really kills the motivation and drive to write if it seems like they won't be acknowledged.

For anyone who wants to put up a general, these are the things you need to know:
-It's the top 14 authors who have updated, not stories, because some authors do updates on two stories simultaneously. If one of these stories hasn't been updated in awhile it is up to the OP's discretion whether or not it should be removed.
-To find out what the most recent story is, go to the previous thread on the archive and Ctrl+f "pastebin" and work from there. That should give you all the information you need.

This can be very tedious if a lot of stories have been updated or written in a short amount of time but it's something that needs to be done for the overall health and longevity of the general. Everyone makes mistakes, and one here and there is no problem. But it's been happening more often. If putting 10 or even 20 minutes making sure the OP is formatted properly is too much work or you feel you can get everything done with a simple copy and paste, then don't make a new thread. This general has gone through hours and even days without a new thread and it's still one of the most popular generals on /trash/.

Anonymous Sun 14 Apr 2019 23:53:18 No.22512049 Report
Quoted By: >>22512383 >>22512810 >>22512860
>>22510657
>how do I actually get around to finishing writing projects?

I think the truth is you either have the drive to do it or you don't. A lot of people say that just making yourself write a thousand words a day will get you into the habit, and there is a lot of truth to that. But you really need to have an almost autistic obsession on your writing project; as in you think about it every single day for the vast majority of the day. Even if you didn't write anything, you're going to sleep thinking about it and hating yourself because you turned off the computer and you're all tucked in so you better hope you get something written tomorrow.

Last year I finished up a graduate degree, guess what I was thinking about instead of my Masters? That story I was working on. I'm hanging out at a bar with friends? That's right, I'm thinking about that story. I currently don't have a job and very well might have to leave the country? You fucking bet I am thinking about that story. It has to be on your mind constantly, and if it isn't, it's only because there is another story you haven't even started yet that you're thinking about instead.

Anonymous Mon 15 Apr 2019 00:39:38 No.22512860 Report

>>22512049
>But you really need to have an almost autistic obsession on your writing project; as in you think about it every single day for the vast majority of the day. Even if you didn't write anything, you're going to sleep thinking about it and hating yourself because you turned off the computer and you're all tucked in so you better hope you get something written tomorrow
As a writer myself, I'm inclined to agree; I never stop thinking about my characters, their stories, situations, etc., including things about them I may never actually commit to paper. However, I'm also a chronic procrastinator by virtue of having major ADD. In the end, the hardest two things about writing are starting and remaining focused. If you can start, your writing will cascade from your eyeballs out onto paper from there, until you hit a block or become distracted with something else. Exercises cut off from distractions help, but only to an extent. It's something you need to try to do only nearly as much as you think about it. I think about my stories and characters constantly, which helps drive my need to write, but I write maybe less than a tenth of the time I actually spend thinking about writing.
